 debate on Islam in Germany. Finally, Kristina Stoeckl analyses the complex relationship among Europe's new religious conflicts, Russian orthodoxy, American Christian conservatives and the emergence of a European populist right-wing.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 4aGesellschaft. 4aPolitik. 4aReligion.  aReligion.  apolitics.  asociety.1 aAppleby, R. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHovorun, Cyril, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchröter, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelderhuis, Herman J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSelderhuis, Herman J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStoeckl, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb0 cEPUBz97831112300090 cprintz978311122805140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783111229102zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783111229102zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783111229102/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA